Date:   Wed Jun 10 17:45:51 2026 -0700

    I-perm-004 (#1198) slice 3: gap-#18 ACCEPT-path token re-point (PG_SPAN_RESOLVER, single-token)
    
    Default OFF -> byte-identical. When the bounded local-window rescue (gap-#18) ACCEPTS a sentence
    whose narrow cited span did not directly entail, the [#ev] token was left pointing at the ORIGINAL
    mis-pointed span — the idx-9 "shipped bound to a badge/altmetric span while the real support sits
    elsewhere in-row" bug. Slice 3 captures the rescue window's OFFSETS and, on accept, RE-POINTS the
    token to that genuinely-entailing window so the report cites the span that actually grounds the claim.
    
    Safety: the accept SEMANTICS are unchanged (the sentence was already passing via the rescue, which
    numeric/content-matched AND was judged ENTAILED) — only WHICH span the surviving token cites changes,
    to the entailing one. Never a new pass. SINGLE-token scope only (the which-token-to-move
    combinatorics for multi-token sentences are out of scope, matching _try_reanchor v1) and gated on
    PG_SPAN_RESOLVER (OFF -> the token is untouched, byte-identical). Applied at the return only when
    is_verified, so a dropped sentence is never re-pointed. Soft-warning `reanchored_local_window:ev:s-e`.
    
    Behavioral proof (offline, MarkerJudge NEUTRAL-on-narrow/ENTAILED-on-window): a single-token sentence
    whose narrow span clears the content floor but the judge grades NEUTRAL, while the wider local window
    contains the predicate -> rescue accepts; flag OFF keeps the original `[#ev:a:0-37]` token
    (byte-identical), flag ON re-points to a DIFFERENT span that contains the marker + emits
    `reanchored_local_window:`.
    
    Tests: 3 new re-point + 62 across the full faithfulness suite (phase0b gap-#18, rescue-guard, reanchor,
    span-provenance, span_resolver) green; OFF byte-identical (no regression).
    
    Next slice: uncited Path 2 of _try_reanchor (symmetric to slice 2) + #1180 widening prompt + bakeoff;
    then activate PG_SPAN_RESOLVER in the Gate-B slate once the full issue lands.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

